  "response_text": "Given your preference for minimal preparation and dislike of cooking, I've created a healthy meal prep plan that's quick, easy, and requires minimal cooking. This plan focuses on simple, no-cook, or one-pot meals that can be prepared in advance.\n\n**Meal Prep Plan:**\n\n**Breakfast**\n\n1. Overnight oats: Mix together rolled oats, milk, and your choice of nuts, seeds, or fruit in a jar or container. Refrigerate overnight and enjoy in the morning. (5 minutes prep)\n2. Greek yogurt parfait: Layer Greek yogurt, granola, and fresh fruit in a container. (5 minutes prep)\n3. Smoothie packs: Prepare individual smoothie packs by freezing your choice of fruit, spinach, and protein powder in a ziplock bag. Add milk or yogurt when you're ready to blend. (5 minutes prep)\n\n**Lunch**\n\n1. Salad jars: Prepare a week's worth of salad jars by layering mixed greens, vegetables, and protein sources like beans, tuna, or chicken in a jar. Add dressing just before eating. (10 minutes prep)\n2. Whole grain wraps: Fill whole grain wraps with hummus, avocado, cucumber, and spinach. (5 minutes prep)\n3. Soup cups: Prepare a batch of no-cook soup by mixing together canned beans, vegetables, and broth in a container. Heat up when you're ready to eat. (10 minutes prep)\n\n**Dinner**\n\n1. One-pot meals: Prepare a batch of quinoa, brown rice, or lentils with your choice of vegetables and protein sources like beans, chicken, or tofu. Cook in a single pot and portion out for the week. (20 minutes prep)\n2. Slow cooker meals: Prepare a slow cooker meal like chili, stew, or curry by adding all the ingredients to the slow cooker and letting it cook while you're away. (10 minutes prep)\n3. Pre-cooked meals: Use pre-cooked chicken, beef, or tofu and add it to a salad or whole grain wrap for a quick and easy dinner. (5 minutes prep)\n\n**Snacks**\n\n1. Fresh fruit: Wash and portion out fresh fruit like apples, bananas, or berries for a quick snack. (5 minutes prep)\n2. Nuts and seeds: Portion out nuts and seeds like almonds, cashews, or pumpkin seeds for a healthy snack. (5 minutes prep)\n3. Energy balls: Mix together rolled oats, nuts, and dried fruit to create no-bake energy balls. (10 minutes prep)\n\n**Tips and Variations:**\n\n* Use pre-cut or pre-washed vegetables to save time on prep.\n* Swap out protein sources like beans, chicken, or tofu to keep meals interesting.\n* Add different spices or seasonings to change up the flavor of your meals.\n* Use a meal prep container or bag to make it easy to grab and go.\n* Prep meals in bulk and portion out individual servings to save time during the week.\n\n**Sample Meal Prep Schedule:**\n\n* Sunday: Prep overnight oats, salad jars, and one-pot meals for the week.\n* Monday: Prep smoothie packs and whole grain wraps for the week.\n* Tuesday: Prep soup cups and energy balls for the week.\n* Wednesday: Prep slow cooker meals for the week.\n* Thursday: Prep fresh fruit and nuts for the week.\n* Friday: Prep pre-cooked meals and portion out individual servings.\n\nRemember, meal prep is all about finding a system that works for you and your lifestyle. Experiment with different recipes and prep methods to find what works best for you.",
